        },
        {
          "text": "Knowledge Production",
          "bold": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Testimony and oral history",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": " \nThis tag highlights moments where Afro-Peruvian women speak about their lives, experiences, and perspectives. These include narrations of personal experiences. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Ancestral memory ",
          "underline": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "This tag highlights moments where Afro-Peruvian women refer to genealogies, past family histories,  connecting their personal stories to an intergenerational memory\n\n"
        },
        {
          "text": "Material conditions ",
          "bold": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Labor and economy ",
          "underline": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "It refers to the discussions of jobs, types of employment, economic survival, and income-generating activities.\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Education and opportunities",
          "underline": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "It refers to schooling, access to education, expectations, and barriers to social and economic mobility.\n\n"
        },
        {
          "text": "History ",
          "bold": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Colonialism and slavery ",
          "underline": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "It centers on histories that refer to the period from the Spanish conquest in 1532 through the abolition of slavery in 1854. During this time, enslaved Africans and their descendants were forced to work in mines, cities, and agricultural estates, forming the early foundations of Afro-Peruvian communities under rigid racial hierarchies. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Post-Abolition and plantation system ",
          "underline": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "It centers on moments that describe how systems of labor exploitation continued after the abolition of slavery in Peru in 1854. Many Afro-Peruvians moved to work in the "
        },
        {
          "text": "hacienda systems",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": ". This system refers to large agricultural estates where landowners controlled labor and resources, maintaining conditions of economic dependency and inequality despite formal freedom. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Agrarian reformation ",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": "\nReferences to the agrarian reform initiated in 1969, a government-led process that sought to dismantle haciendas and redistribute land to workers and rural communities. This reform aimed to reduce inequality and transform rural labor relations, significantly affecting Afro-Peruvian populations who had long worked on these estates. This period also includes broader political changes, such as expanded citizenship rights formalized in the 1979 Constitution. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "More about the agrarian reformation\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Post-Agrarian reformation",
          "underline": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Discussions of the outcomes and limitations of the agrarian reformation, including the creation of cooperatives (collective farming organizations), new forms of community leadership, and the persistence of economic inequality despite structural changes.\n\n"
        },
        {
          "text": "Afro-Peruvian culture ",
          "bold": true
        }
